When the correct payload is used:

```text
http://[VM-IP]/?page=media&src=data:text/html,<script>flag13</script>
```

or its base‑64 equivalent:

```text
http://[VM-IP]/?page=media&src=data:text/html;base64,PHNjcmlwdD5mbGFnMTM8L3NjcmlwdD4K
```

the Darkly application recognizes that the `flag13` script has executed and returns the flag string. This is typically visible either:
- Directly on the page, as a `FLAG: ...` message, or
- As a newly “unlocked” file in the `13-XSS_data_uri/flag` path, which can be inspected afterward to confirm the breach is complete.

The final outcome is that the attacker has successfully:
- Injected a script into a `data:` URI.
- Passed it through the `src` parameter of the `media` page.
- Triggered the script in the browser, satisfying the lab’s flag‑unlocking logic.

This completes breach 13 and demonstrates that even non‑script‑like parameters such as `src` can become XSS vectors if they accept data‑URI‑style content.

